3. Use buyer phrases from Section 5 naturally — speak their language
4. Address buying objections directly — do not hedge or avoid them
5. Honest cons build trust — include them, then counter with why the product is still the right buy
6. Discount codes placed near CTAs — mention naturally, not as a standalone paragraph
7. Primary keyword in `<strong>` tags every mention — no exceptions
8. No editorial literary hooks — open sections with the buyer benefit or buying question directly
9. H2 sections are short and direct — buyers scan, they do not read long intros
10. Conclusion = final push to purchase — not a summary, a decision driver
11. Internal links placed mid-post after first product CTA — anchor text natural, never forced
12. No related articles section — handled by site component
13. Language: American English only — no British English spellings
14. No banned AI patterns: no "elevate," "seamlessly," "game-changing," "dive into," "transformative"
15. No long em dashes — use comma or restructure sentence
16. Sentence rhythm varies — short punchy sentences for key selling points, longer for context
17. No "we tested" language — informed editorial observations from specs and real buyer reviews only
18. Product 2 (MB420G Gift Box) and Product 5 (SM200F Plus Drill Set) have no ratings — write 2–3 editorial lines per product based on specs and description. Tone: informed editorial. Example: "The MB420G Gift Box is built for the nail lover who already knows what she wants — a 40,000 RPM motor and a professional UV lamp, in a package that feels like opening something from a high-end salon."
